<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-11-14T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-11-14T15:00:00-05:00" n="365" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 184.13/128: Telegram</note>
                    <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                                <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss></hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-11-14T15:00:00-05:00">November 14, 1919—3
                            p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 15—12:50 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                    <p>3762. For Polk. Your 5123, November 11, 9 p.m. It has been found impossible
                        to have U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">George Washington</hi> make another trip,
                        but the U. S. S. <hi rend="italic">America</hi> operated by the War
                        Department will be at Brest on or about December 1st. Arrangements will be
                        made with the War Department for shipping all Mission files, documents,
                        etc., on the steamer <hi rend="italic">America</hi> if you so desire.</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>